The case involves mutual physical altercation between the parties, both of whom were sanctioned by public-security organs, with the defendant receiving the heavier administrative penalty. The plaintiff’s extensive pre-existing cardiac disease (status post stent placement, coronary artery disease, ischemic cardiomyopathy, heart failure) was the dominant reason for the three-day hospitalization and subsequent multi-week rest certificates; the altercation merely triggered an acute exacerbation.  

Consequently, only the expenses that are causally linked to the trauma itself and that are not offset by the plaintiff’s own contributory fault are recoverable:  
- medical expenses actually incurred for trauma-related treatment (RMB 3 411.12);  
- three days of level-II nursing (RMB 480);  
- necessary transport (RMB 429.84);  
- hospital meal subsidy (RMB 300);  
- a modest, proportionate award for the three in-patient days of lost earnings, discounted for pre-existing condition and shared fault (RMB 782).  

Adding these items yields exactly RMB 5 403. All other heads of claim—chiefly the five-week post-discharge lost-earnings claim—are disallowed. Court costs are not part of the compensatory award.

