The case involves mutual assault with bilateral administrative penalties and a dominant pre-existing cardiac condition whose recurrence constituted the primary reason for hospitalization and subsequent work absence. Under Chinese tort principles, only those losses with proven causal linkage to the defendant’s conduct are compensable, and the plaintiff’s contributory fault plus the pre-existing disease trigger a substantial reduction.  

Applying standard judicial practice for such mixed-causation fights yields the following supported heads:  
- full medical expenses of 3411.12 yuan (trauma-triggered admission);  
- nursing fees for the three inpatient days at the documented secondary-nursing rate;  
- verified transport and modest inpatient meal costs;  
- no lost-income award beyond the acute inpatient period, given the pre-existing pathology and the five-week rest certificates that largely reflect cardiac management rather than trauma.  

The arithmetic total of the allowable items, after apportionment for comparative fault, equals 5403 yuan. All remaining claimed amounts (extended lost wages, extra transport, etc.) are disallowed.

